So life presents itself as a series of external 
obstacles and events. And it feels very much  

539
00:50:11,920 --> 00:50:19,640
like an external journey. And it can feel that way 
your whole life. But I think what you'll realize,  

540
00:50:19,640 --> 00:50:27,040
and I started realizing this when I really 
started meditating and spending time distancing  

541
00:50:27,040 --> 00:50:37,360
myself from the subconscious thoughts, is a very, 
very large part of life is internal. I say a very  

542
00:50:37,360 --> 00:50:42,800
large part because obviously you need some 
food, clothing, shelter, some basic needs that  

543
00:50:42,800 --> 00:50:49,840
are external. But for most people that have the 
ability to even listen to this podcast, I would  

544
00:50:49,840 --> 00:50:56,640
say the vast majority of your life is internal.
So what do I mean by that? I mean that you're  

545
00:50:56,640 --> 00:51:05,160
writing a story about what it is you think you 
need to be happy, or you're writing a story about  

546
00:51:05,160 --> 00:51:13,280
things you think you need to be to be enough 
or to be respected or to feel worthy or to get  

547
00:51:13,280 --> 00:51:20,840
admiration of other people. You're writing that 
story, and it's just a story. And if you really  

548
00:51:20,840 --> 00:51:27,400
follow this logic, you'll realize that. You'll 
realize it is 100% just a story, or it's a story  

549
00:51:27,400 --> 00:51:36,040
that you should even care. And then that opens 
up a lot more agency that you have over deciding  

550
00:51:36,040 --> 00:51:41,720
what is important to you, what is your internal 
scorecard, what are the things that matter to you,  

551
00:51:42,400 --> 00:51:48,840
not what the external world thinks or the story 
you've been writing for a long time. When you  

552
00:51:48,840 --> 00:51:56,520
start to open this up, it's really kind of scary 
at first, because you'll start to realize most of  

553
00:51:58,080 --> 00:52:02,040
the things you're operating from are 
really just stories that have been  

554
00:52:02,040 --> 00:52:07,920
written at some point in your life. And 
so it's actually terrifying at first,  

555
00:52:07,920 --> 00:52:10,880
and then it starts to become really liberating.

556
00:52:10,880 --> 00:52:13,480
Was there an example of that in 
your life? Because externally,  

557
00:52:13,480 --> 00:52:16,000
it feels like you're killing it: a killer PE fund,  

558
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:21,640
teaching at Stanford. The scorecard is looking 
good. So it's interesting you say that.

559
00:52:21,640 --> 00:52:30,960
The first time I really realized this, it 
was in 2015. I mentioned to you it took  

560
00:52:30,960 --> 00:52:36,600
me 14 years to be successful. So we had just 
sold the last company from our second fund,  

561
00:52:36,600 --> 00:52:43,000
which is where we really got paid. I had a 
financial event that was ... it wasn't like  

562
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:47,200
I never have to work again in my life. It was 
just like I could exhale a little bit. I knew  

563
00:52:47,200 --> 00:52:51,160
I was going to be able to pay my mortgage and 
put my kids through college. It was that kind  

564
00:52:51,160 --> 00:52:56,760
of an event. And for a couple days I was 
euphoric, because I felt like I'd worked  

565
00:52:56,760 --> 00:53:00,160
so hard for this. I'd been, again, at this 
for 15 years, but really longer than that,  

566
00:53:00,160 --> 00:53:05,800
if you go back to getting into college. And 
the whole thing had been a long journey. 

567
00:53:05,800 --> 00:53:13,680
And then it hit me that nothing changed. 
Nothing internally changed at all. I still  

568
00:53:13,680 --> 00:53:20,680
had the same problems. I still felt the same 
way about myself. I still had a lot of negative  

569
00:53:20,680 --> 00:53:26,600
thoughts about myself. This goal that I thought 
that I had for this whole long period of time,  

570
00:53:26,600 --> 00:53:32,480
it didn't actually change anything. It 
changed externally, for sure. Like I said,  

571
00:53:32,480 --> 00:53:38,800
I could exhale and pay my mortgage. And those are 
all really good things. But that was the first  

572
00:53:38,800 --> 00:53:45,720
time when I realized, "Oh, wait a second. It's 
really up to me to find things that are going  

573
00:53:45,720 --> 00:53:54,320
to give me joy. And the achievement of some kind 
of external event is not one of those things." 

574
00:53:54,320 --> 00:54:00,280
And I know that sounds really, really weird, but 
there's so many people that I've heard that have  

575
00:54:00,280 --> 00:54:06,160
had very, very similar stories. And so it was 
really disorienting for me. And actually it was  

576
00:54:06,160 --> 00:54:11,320
the first time in my life where I experienced 
depression, because I just had this thought of,  

577
00:54:14,520 --> 00:54:18,120
"I think I was working my whole life for 
that, and it wasn't what I thought it was  

578
00:54:18,120 --> 00:54:25,000
going to be." And so now I was thinking, 
"Well, what is it then? What is the thing  

579
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:34,840
that's going to give me joy?" And that takes 
some introspection to ask those questions.

580
00:54:34,840 --> 00:54:38,400
I was just having a conversation with 
a friend who's an angel investor,  

581
00:54:38,400 --> 00:54:42,840
and he just had a bunch of exits. And he's like, 
"Cool, I got some money in my bank account now,  

582
00:54:42,840 --> 00:54:46,840
but I don't feel anything. I 
thought I'd be like, 'Holy moly,  

583
00:54:47,800 --> 00:54:52,120
this is exactly what I was hoping for. And 
nothing changed.'" Exactly how you're describing.

584
00:54:53,720 --> 00:54:59,680
I think you get a little bit of peace of 
mind when you have some financial security,  

585
00:54:59,680 --> 00:55:07,560
which is valuable. But in terms of now my 
life changes, now I'm enough, now I am happy,  

586
00:55:07,560 --> 00:55:15,040
now I feel good about myself, none of that 
changes, for really anybody that I know.

587
00:55:15,040 --> 00:55:17,560
And the hardest part, as you said, 
is you think it will. You think, "Oh,  

588
00:55:17,560 --> 00:55:21,440
I'll be so happy once I achieve this thing." 
And I think an example of this is there's a  

589
00:55:21,440 --> 00:55:26,200
lot of miserable billionaires, from what I've 
read and see. And that should tell you a lot.

590
00:55:26,200 --> 00:55:27,840
Yeah, exactly.

591
00:55:27,840 --> 00:55:33,800
Maybe a second-to-last question; I'm curious 
if there's anything recently you're focused on,  

592
00:55:33,800 --> 00:55:36,280
have been thinking a lot about that 
maybe you changed your mind about,  

593
00:55:36,280 --> 00:55:38,720
or has changed the way you think about the world?

594
00:55:38,720 --> 00:55:46,800
The last two years, I had my two oldest boys 
go off to college, 2022 and then 2024. And  

595
00:55:46,800 --> 00:55:52,240
that really hit hard. You would think that I 
would've been preparing for that for 18 years  

596
00:55:52,240 --> 00:56:00,200
for each of them, but for some reason it just 
really hit me really, really hard. And I think  

597
00:56:00,200 --> 00:56:09,600
it was a real wake up call of mortality, I 
guess, and to realize that nothing goes on  

598
00:56:09,600 --> 00:56:15,080
forever. And these wonderful people that I had 
lived with, each for 18 years, were no longer  

599
00:56:15,080 --> 00:56:23,320
going to really be a part of my daily life.
And that really set me off on a journey of a  

600
00:56:23,320 --> 00:56:31,480
lot of spiritual work, doing a lot of meditating 
and working with some gurus. And it's been really  

601
00:56:31,480 --> 00:56:42,147
profound. And it's put me a lot closer in touch 
with the things that really matter to me. I've  

602
00:56:42,147 --> 00:56:50,080
given myself more permission to spend time doing 
those things than the normal external world type  

603
00:56:50,080 --> 00:57:01,440
things. So that was a pretty profound change for 
me. And the spiritual journey is arguably really  

604
00:57:01,440 --> 00:57:09,000
the important journey. And this could be a longer 
conversation. And maybe you have the luxury of  

605
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:17,720
doing that journey as you get older or something, 
but it's been a really profound, profound journey.

606
00:57:17,720 --> 00:57:22,680
I'm excited to see what insights come out of this 
part of your life. Final question before we get to  

607
00:57:22,680 --> 00:57:27,880
our very exciting lightning round. We have this 
segment on the podcast called Failure Corner,  

608
00:57:27,880 --> 00:57:32,440
where people come on this podcast, they share 
all these wins: "Oh, I have this amazing PE  

609
00:57:32,440 --> 00:57:36,120
fund that's killing it. I teach at Stanford. I've 
launched all these things. All these students,  

610
00:57:36,120 --> 00:57:43,200
they're so great. Life's amazing. Nothing ever 
goes wrong," when in reality, it does. And those  

611
00:57:43,200 --> 00:57:47,200
stories often aren't told. So I'm curious 
if there's a story you could share of a time  

612
00:57:47,200 --> 00:57:51,200
you failed in your career and, if you learned 
something from that experience, what you learned.

613
00:57:51,200 --> 00:57:56,120
Yeah, I'll tell a couple stories. So 
when I was in high school, I wrestled.  

614
00:57:57,040 --> 00:58:03,000
And I cut a lot of weight to make the 
varsity team. And I was not in the best  

615
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:09,000
mental place because of cutting weight. But 
anyway, I lost a big match my junior year.  

616
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:14,320
And I quit and I never wrestled again. 
And that haunted me. So first of all,  

617
00:58:14,320 --> 00:58:23,520
that was a failure, a big failure for me. And 
it really haunted me. And so I, after that,  

618
00:58:24,120 --> 00:58:29,400
made a promise to myself that it wasn't going to 
have that happen again. When I went to college,  

619
00:58:29,400 --> 00:58:36,080
I tried to row crew. I failed year after year 
trying to make the team, trying to make the boat.  

620
00:58:37,240 --> 00:58:43,960
Eventually had some real success my senior year, 
but prior to that, just failure after failure. 

621
00:58:43,960 --> 00:58:50,960
And then at Alpine, I mean, we lost money on 
our first fund. We had real trouble during the  

622
00:58:50,960 --> 00:58:57,720
recession. I think five of my first eight 
investments I ever made in my life, I lost  

623
00:58:57,720 --> 00:59:03,400
money. And in venture world, that's one thing, but 
in private equity, that's a whole different ratio,  

624
00:59:03,400 --> 00:59:13,080
which is not a good ratio at all. When I first 
started teaching, I wasn't good at teaching,  

625
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:19,080
had a lot of insecurities. I was really 
young when I started, and I didn't feel  

626
00:59:19,080 --> 00:59:25,120
like I had really anything to share with the 
students. And I think that showed up, and it  

627
00:59:25,120 --> 00:59:33,520
took me a long time to kind of figure that out.
So I guess almost my entire track record is one  

628
00:59:33,520 --> 00:59:42,320
that starts with things not going well, and then 
just over a long period of time of chipping away,  

629
00:59:42,320 --> 00:59:50,400
looks like a success on paper. But anytime early 
in the process would look like an abject failure.  

630
00:59:50,400 --> 00:59:58,320
So I'm quite familiar with failure in the form 
of setbacks. I think the ultimate failure though  

631
00:59:58,320 --> 01:00:03,280
was the wrestling one, where I just quit. That 
was really the only one I would characterize as  

632
01:00:03,280 --> 01:00:11,000
a failure. The other ones, because I kept going 
and staying with it, turned out to work out well,  

633
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:15,240
with a lot of scars and bruises, but 
the failure would've been quitting.

634
01:00:15,240 --> 01:00:20,920
I love that the circles back to your core 
advice of stick with it. Most things that  

635
01:00:20,920 --> 01:00:24,314
are important take a long time and there's 
a lot of suffering [inaudible 01:00:24].

636
01:00:24,314 --> 01:00:26,360
Yeah, they do. Yeah.

637
01:00:26,360 --> 01:00:29,600
Something I wanted to ask, I can't help 
but ask at this point, because I think a  

638
01:00:29,600 --> 01:00:33,480
lot of people are wondering this, just when 
do you quit? When should you quit something?  

639
01:00:33,480 --> 01:00:37,200
Because some things are just not worth it. 
Is there any advice there you could share?

640
01:00:37,200 --> 01:00:44,240
Yes, for sure. I think the time to quit is 
when you can no longer see the vision and  

641
01:00:44,240 --> 01:00:49,120
you can no longer really believe the vision. 
And then when that happens for a long period  

642
01:00:49,120 --> 01:00:54,800
of time ... or maybe you're no longer even 
excited about the vision; somewhere in there,  

643
01:00:54,800 --> 01:00:59,680
I think. The excited one, you have to be a 
little careful of, because in the dark days,  

644
01:00:59,680 --> 01:01:05,800
exciting is not the word you're going to use. 
But at least in our company, for the first 10  

645
01:01:05,800 --> 01:01:13,440
years it was not going well. But each time, we'd 
make fewer mistakes, we'd start to see something  

646
01:01:13,440 --> 01:01:18,120
working. We'd do one really good deal in this 
fund, we'd start to learn from that. We'd get one  

647
01:01:18,120 --> 01:01:24,560
really good hire, we'd learn from that. We would 
little by little start to see these green shoots. 

648
01:01:24,560 --> 01:01:33,720
And I have this unbelievable statement. I didn't 
write it. Dan and Chip Heath wrote it in their  

649
01:01:33,720 --> 01:01:39,520
book, Switch, which is "Scale your bright spots. 
Find what's working and do more of that." And as  

650
01:01:39,520 --> 01:01:44,440
you start to progress, for me, for example, at 
Alpine, almost all the time, we always had at  

651
01:01:44,440 --> 01:01:49,800
least a small glimmer of a bright spot. And then 
we'd scale that and then we'd continue forward and  

652
01:01:49,800 --> 01:01:56,160
we'd find some more and we'd scale those. And over 
time, all those bright spots became our business.  

653
01:01:56,160 --> 01:01:59,880
That became what we did. That became our 
strategy. That became how we hired people.  

654
01:01:59,880 --> 01:02:05,960
That became where we recruited from. All those 
bright spots just started to magnify until the  

655
01:02:06,920 --> 01:02:12,800
entire business was pretty much a bright spot. 
But it took time, because we had to figure out  

656
01:02:12,800 --> 01:02:18,920
where those were. And we had to do a lot of things 
wrong to figure out where the bright spots were.

657
01:02:18,920 --> 01:02:22,400
Graham, is there anything else that you 
wanted to share or you think is important  

658
01:02:22,400 --> 01:02:26,120
to leave listeners with before we get 
to our very exciting lightning round?

659
01:02:26,120 --> 01:02:32,680
I mean, I think what I would say is 
just in general, you got one life,  

660
01:02:32,680 --> 01:02:37,880
you get one shot. And so take the time to 
really figure out and answer the question,  

661
01:02:37,880 --> 01:02:43,400
what does a wonderful, amazing, incredible life 
look like? And just get as clear as you possibly  

662
01:02:43,400 --> 01:02:49,360
can on that. No matter how crazy or aspirational 
it seems, write it down. Write down that thing  

663
01:02:49,360 --> 01:02:55,480
is write down that thing that would make this 
life amazing. And write it down for your life,  

664
01:02:55,480 --> 01:02:58,680
your career, your relationships, your 
friends, your body, your spirituality,  

665
01:02:58,680 --> 01:03:07,160
your financial situation. And just the first magic 
is just knowing what you want. And I'd say 90% of  

666
01:03:07,160 --> 01:03:12,960
people never even know what they want. So take 
the time to do that. And the more clear you are  

667
01:03:12,960 --> 01:03:18,440
on that, the more invested you are in that, 
the more likely you are to make it come true.

668
01:03:18,440 --> 01:03:21,640
What I love about that is you 
don't have to do this thing,  

669
01:03:21,640 --> 01:03:26,900
just step one is understand what 
it could be if you could do that.

670
01:03:26,900 --> 01:03:27,320
Exactly.

671
01:03:27,320 --> 01:03:30,360
And it's almost like understand where 
your Google directions could take you  

672
01:03:30,360 --> 01:03:34,320
if you turned off autopilot. Oh, man. Okay. Well,  

673
01:03:34,320 --> 01:03:37,080
with that, Graham, we reached our very 
exciting lightning round. Are you ready?

